      "content": "Hey! You’re asking a great question about why feature scaling matters when you have features like age (0–100) and annual income (0–200,000). The difference in range can actually be a problem for many machine learning algorithms, so let’s break it down.  \n\nFirst, most algorithms—like linear regression, logistic regression, or even neural networks—calculate distances or gradients that are sensitive to the scale of the input features. If one feature has a much larger range than the other, the algorithm might “pay more attention” to the larger feature simply because its values are bigger, not because it’s more important.  \n\nThink of it like a goblin who’s trying to measure how far a stone is from a castle. If the goblin’s ruler is in meters and the stone is 500 meters away, but the castle is 50 meters away, the goblin might mistakenly think the stone is farther just because the number is bigger, even if the distance is actually the same. Scaling normalizes the features so that each one contributes fairly to the calculation, regardless of its original range.  \n\nIn your case, age is roughly 0–100 and income is",
